565.answer:
Merge sort is a divide-and-conquer sorting algorithm:

1. Split the array into two halves.
2. Recursively sort each half.
3. Merge the two sorted halves into one sorted array.

Why it is **O(n log n)**:
- Each split cuts the problem size roughly in half, so there are about **log n** levels of recursion.
- At each level, merging all subarrays together processes each element once, which costs **O(n)** total.
- So the total work is **O(n)** per level × **O(log n)** levels = **O(n log n)**.

Example JavaScript implementation:

```js
function mergeSort(arr) {
  if (arr.length <= 1) return arr;

  const mid = Math.floor(arr.length / 2);
  const left = mergeSort(arr.slice(0, mid));
  const right = mergeSort(arr.slice(mid));

  return merge(left, right);
}

function merge(left, right) {
  const result = [];
  let i = 0;
  let j = 0;

  while (i < left.length && j < right.length) {
    if (left[i] <= right[j]) {
      result.push(left[i]);
      i++;
    } else {
      result.push(right[j]);
      j++;
    }
  }

  while (i < left.length) {
    result.push(left[i]);
    i++;
  }

  while (j < right.length) {
    result.push(right[j]);
    j++;
  }

  return result;
}

// Example:
console.log(mergeSort([5, 2, 9, 1, 3, 7])); // [1, 2, 3, 5, 7, 9]
```

