576.answer:
A trie is a tree for storing strings by shared prefixes.

- Each edge/step represents a character.
- Each node represents a prefix.
- A flag on a node marks whether a full word ends there.

Example: storing `cat`, `car`, and `dog` shares the `ca` path for the first two words.

It helps with:
- **Fast prefix queries**: check whether any word starts with a prefix like `app`.
- **Dictionary lookups**: search whole words efficiently.
- **Autocomplete**: find words beginning with typed characters.
- **Reducing repeated prefix storage**: common prefixes are shared.

Compared with a hash set:
- A hash set is great for exact word lookup.
- A trie is better when you also need prefix operations like `startsWith`.

### JavaScript implementation

```js
class TrieNode {
  constructor() {
    this.children = new Map();
    this.isWord = false;
  }
}

class Trie {
  constructor() {
    this.root = new TrieNode();
  }

  insert(word) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const char of word) {
      if (!node.children.has(char)) {
        node.children.set(char, new TrieNode());
      }
      node = node.children.get(char);
    }

    node.isWord = true;
  }

  search(word) {
    const node = this._traverse(word);
    return node !== null && node.isWord;
  }

  startsWith(prefix) {
    return this._traverse(prefix) !== null;
  }

  _traverse(str) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const char of str) {
      if (!node.children.has(char)) {
        return null;
      }
      node = node.children.get(char);
    }

    return node;
  }
}

// Example
const trie = new Trie();
trie.insert("apple");

console.log(trie.search("apple"));    // true
console.log(trie.search("app"));      // false
console.log(trie.startsWith("app"));  // true
trie.insert("app");
console.log(trie.search("app"));      // true
```

### Time complexity
- `insert(word)`: **O(n)**
- `search(word)`: **O(n)**
- `startsWith(prefix)`: **O(n)**

Where `n` is the length of the input string.

