Debouncing collapses bursts of events into a single action. Each call resets a timer, and the callback runs only after events have stopped for the configured delay. In event-driven systems, that prevents expensive work from firing on every keystroke, resize, or scroll event and instead waits for a quiet period.

```js
function debounce(callback, delay = 300) {
  let timerId;

  return function debounced(...args) {
    const context = this;
    clearTimeout(timerId);
    timerId = setTimeout(() => {
      callback.apply(context, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}
```

Example:

```js
