`PUT` is idempotent because making the same request multiple times should leave the resource in the same final state as making it once. If `PUT /users/123` with the same full JSON body is repeated, the user record should still end up exactly matching that body — no duplicate users, no incremental side effects.

Example Express handler:

```js
import express from 'express';

const app = express();
app.use(express.json());

const users = new Map();

app.put('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
  const { id } = req.params;
  const replacement = req.body;

  const user = {
    id,
    ...replacement,
  };

  users.set(id, user);

  res.status(200).json(user);
});
```

If you want stricter replacement semantics, don’t let the body override the path ID:

```js
app.put('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
  const { id } = req.params;

  const user = {
    ...req.body,
    id,
  };

  users.set(id, user);
  res.status(200).json(user);
});
```

Behavior:
- `PUT` replaces the whole user resource.
- The URL identifies which user is being replaced.
- Repeating the same request produces the same stored record.
- If the user does not exist yet, many APIs create it and return `201`; otherwise `200` or `204` is common.

If you want, I can also give you a version with validation and proper `200` vs `201` behavior.

