Markdown headings use `#` prefixes at the start of a line: `#` for level 1, `##` for level 2, up to `######` for level 6. A heading’s nesting is determined by its level number, so an `h3` belongs under the nearest preceding `h2`, and an `h2` belongs under the nearest preceding `h1`. In practice, a table of contents parser walks headings in order and uses a stack to place each heading under the correct parent.

```js
function parseMarkdownToc(markdown) {
  const lines = markdown.split(/\r?\n/);
  const roots = [];
  const stack = [];

  for (const line of lines) {
    const match = line.match(/^(#{1,6})\s+(.*?)\s*#*\s*$/);
    if (!match) continue;

    const level = match[1].length;
    const title = match[2].trim();
    const node = { title, level, children: [] };

    while (stack.length && stack[stack.length - 1].level >= level) {
      stack.pop();
    }

    if (stack.length === 0) {
      roots.push(node);
    } else {
      stack[stack.length - 1].children.push(node);
    }

    stack.push(node);
  }

  return roots;
}
```

Example:

```js
const md = `
# Title
## Getting Started
### Install
## Usage
### Basic
#### Advanced
# Appendix
`;

console.log(JSON.stringify(parseMarkdownToc(md), null, 2));
```

