A monotonic queue is a deque that keeps its elements in sorted order as you push new items, so the best candidate for each window is always at the front.

For a **sliding window maximum**, use a **decreasing deque** of indices:

- When adding a new element `nums[i]`, remove indices from the back while `nums[back] <= nums[i]`.
- Push `i` at the back.
- Remove the front index if it is outside the current window.
- Once the first full window is formed, the front of the deque is the maximum for that window.

Why it works:
- The deque stays decreasing by value, so the front is always the largest.
- Smaller elements behind a larger incoming element are useless and get discarded.
- Each index is added and removed at most once, so the total time is **O(n)**.

```js
function maxSlidingWindow(nums, k) {
  if (k <= 0 || nums.length === 0) return [];

  const deque = []; // stores indices, values are decreasing
  const result = [];

  for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    while (deque.length && deque[0] <= i - k) {
      deque.shift();
    }

    while (deque.length && nums[deque[deque.length - 1]] <= nums[i]) {
      deque.pop();
    }

    deque.push(i);

    if (i >= k - 1) {
      result.push(nums[deque[0]]);
    }
  }

  return result;
}
```

Example:

```js
console.log(maxSlidingWindow([1, 3, -1, -3, 5, 3, 6, 7], 3));
// [3, 3, 5, 5, 6, 7]
```

