789.answer:
The Strategy pattern defines a family of algorithms, puts each one in its own class/object, and makes them interchangeable at runtime. It’s useful when you want to swap behavior without filling your code with `if/else` or `switch` logic.

### Core idea
- **Context**: the object that uses a strategy
- **Strategy interface**: a shared contract each strategy follows
- **Concrete strategies**: different implementations of that contract

In your payment example:
- the **context** is a checkout/payment processor
- the **strategies** are credit card, PayPal, and bank transfer payment handlers

### JavaScript example
```js
class CreditCardPayment {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using Credit Card.`);
  }
}

class PayPalPayment {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using PayPal.`);
  }
}

class BankTransferPayment {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using Bank Transfer.`);
  }
}

class PaymentProcessor {
  constructor(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  setStrategy(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  processPayment(amount) {
    if (!this.strategy || typeof this.strategy.pay !== 'function') {
      throw new Error('A valid payment strategy is required.');
    }

    this.strategy.pay(amount);
  }
}

// Usage
const processor = new PaymentProcessor(new CreditCardPayment());
processor.processPayment(100);

processor.setStrategy(new PayPalPayment());
processor.processPayment(75);

processor.setStrategy(new BankTransferPayment());
processor.processPayment(250);
```

### Why this is useful
- avoids large conditional blocks
- makes adding new payment methods easy
- keeps each payment behavior isolated
- lets you switch payment logic at runtime

