The Factory Method pattern defines an interface or abstract type for creating objects, while letting subclasses or a dedicated factory decide which concrete implementation to instantiate. It helps remove `new` calls from client code, keeps object-creation logic centralized, and makes it easier to add new variants without changing the code that uses them.

### When to use it
- You have multiple implementations of the same interface.
- Client code should depend on abstractions, not concrete classes.
- You want a single place to choose which implementation to create.

### Java example: notification senders
```java
interface NotificationSender {
    void send(String recipient, String message);
}

class EmailSender implements NotificationSender {
    @Override
    public void send(String recipient, String message) {
        System.out.println("Sending EMAIL to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

class SmsSender implements NotificationSender {
    @Override
    public void send(String recipient, String message) {
        System.out.println("Sending SMS to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

class PushSender implements NotificationSender {
    @Override
    public void send(String recipient, String message) {
        System.out.println("Sending PUSH notification to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

enum NotificationType {
    EMAIL,
    SMS,
    PUSH
}

class NotificationFactory {
    public static NotificationSender createSender(NotificationType type) {
        return switch (type) {
            case EMAIL -> new EmailSender();
            case SMS -> new SmsSender();
            case PUSH -> new PushSender();
        };
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        NotificationSender emailSender = NotificationFactory.createSender(NotificationType.EMAIL);
        NotificationSender smsSender = NotificationFactory.createSender(NotificationType.SMS);
        NotificationSender pushSender = NotificationFactory.createSender(NotificationType.PUSH);

        emailSender.send("alice@example.com", "Welcome!");
        smsSender.send("+1234567890", "Your code is 123456");
        pushSender.send("user-device-42", "You have a new message");
    }
}
```

### Why this is Factory Method
- `NotificationSender` is the common product interface.
- `EmailSender`, `SmsSender`, and `PushSender` are concrete products.
- `NotificationFactory.createSender(...)` centralizes creation logic.
- Client code only asks for a sender type and uses the interface.

If you want, I can also show the classic **inheritance-based** Factory Method version with an abstract creator class.

