The adapter pattern lets incompatible interfaces work together by wrapping one object with another interface your app expects.

In your case, the app wants JSON, but the legacy service speaks XML. An adapter sits in between:

- **Target interface**: the JSON-based API your modern code uses
- **Adaptee**: the legacy XML service
- **Adapter**: converts JSON requests to XML, calls the legacy service, then converts XML responses back to JSON

### Why use it
- Keeps legacy code unchanged
- Avoids spreading XML handling across the codebase
- Makes migration incremental
- Improves testability by coding against the target interface

### TypeScript example

```ts
// Target interface: what the modern app wants
interface UserService {
  getUser(id: string): Promise<{ id: string; name: string; email: string }>;
}

// Legacy XML service: incompatible interface
class LegacyXmlUserService {
  async fetchUser(xmlRequest: string): Promise<string> {
    // Simulated legacy XML API
    // Example request: <GetUserRequest><Id>123</Id></GetUserRequest>

    const idMatch = xmlRequest.match(/<Id>(.*?)<\/Id>/);
    const id = idMatch?.[1] ?? "unknown";

    return `
      <GetUserResponse>
        <User>
          <Id>${id}</Id>
          <Name>Jane Doe</Name>
          <Email>jane@example.com</Email>
        </User>
      </GetUserResponse>
    `.trim();
  }
}

// Adapter: converts JSON-style calls into XML requests/responses
class XmlToJsonUserServiceAdapter implements UserService {
  constructor(private readonly legacyService: LegacyXmlUserService) {}

  async getUser(id: string): Promise<{ id: string; name: string; email: string }> {
    const xmlRequest = this.toXmlRequest(id);
    const xmlResponse = await this.legacyService.fetchUser(xmlRequest);
    return this.fromXmlResponse(xmlResponse);
  }

  private toXmlRequest(id: string): string {
    return `<GetUserRequest><Id>${this.escapeXml(id)}</Id></GetUserRequest>`;
  }

  private fromXmlResponse(xml: string): { id: string; name: string; email: string } {
    return {
      id: this.extractTag(xml, "Id"),
      name: this.extractTag(xml, "Name"),
      email: this.extractTag(xml, "Email"),
    };
  }

  private extractTag(xml: string, tag: string): string {
    const match = xml.match(new RegExp(`<${tag}>(.*?)<\\/${tag}>`));
    if (!match) {
      throw new Error(`Missing <${tag}> in XML response`);
    }
    return match[1];
  }

  private escapeXml(value: string): string {
    return value
      .replace(/&/g, "&amp;")
      .replace(/</g, "&lt;")
      .replace(/>/g, "&gt;")
      .replace(/"/g, "&quot;")
      .replace(/'/g, "&apos;");
  }
}

// Client code uses only the JSON-friendly interface
async function main() {
  const legacyService = new LegacyXmlUserService();
  const userService: UserService = new XmlToJsonUserServiceAdapter(legacyService);

  const user = await userService.getUser("123");
  console.log(user);
  // { id: '123', name: 'Jane Doe', email: 'jane@example.com' }
}

main();
```

### What this achieves
The client never deals with XML directly. If you later replace the legacy service with a native JSON service, you can keep the same `UserService` interface and swap implementations.

If you want, I can also provide:
- a version using `DOMParser` or `fast-xml-parser`
- a more realistic HTTP example
- unit tests for the adapter

