The Command pattern turns requests into objects so you can parameterize actions, queue them, log them, and support undo without the caller knowing the receiver details.

- **Command**: an object with a common interface like `execute()` and `undo()`.
- **Receiver**: the thing that does the real work, like a `Light`.
- **Invoker**: triggers commands, like a remote control.
- **Client**: wires everything together.

This is useful when you want to decouple *what button was pressed* from *what action happens*, and especially when you want history/undo.

```js
class Light {
  constructor(location) {
    this.location = location;
    this.isOn = false;
  }

  on() {
    this.isOn = true;
    console.log(`${this.location} light is ON`);
  }

  off() {
    this.isOn = false;
    console.log(`${this.location} light is OFF`);
  }
}

class LightOnCommand {
  constructor(light) {
    this.light = light;
  }

  execute() {
    this.light.on();
  }

  undo() {
    this.light.off();
  }
}

class LightOffCommand {
  constructor(light) {
    this.light = light;
  }

  execute() {
    this.light.off();
  }

  undo() {
    this.light.on();
  }
}

class NoCommand {
  execute() {}
  undo() {}
}

class RemoteControl {
  constructor() {
    this.onCommand = new NoCommand();
    this.offCommand = new NoCommand();
    this.lastCommand = new NoCommand();
  }

  setCommands(onCommand, offCommand) {
    this.onCommand = onCommand;
    this.offCommand = offCommand;
  }

  pressOn() {
    this.onCommand.execute();
    this.lastCommand = this.onCommand;
  }

  pressOff() {
    this.offCommand.execute();
    this.lastCommand = this.offCommand;
  }

  pressUndo() {
    this.lastCommand.undo();
  }
}

// Usage
const livingRoomLight = new Light('Living Room');

const lightOn = new LightOnCommand(livingRoomLight);
const lightOff = new LightOffCommand(livingRoomLight);

const remote = new RemoteControl();
remote.setCommands(lightOn, lightOff);

remote.pressOn();   // Living Room light is ON
remote.pressOff();  // Living Room light is OFF
remote.pressUndo(); // Living Room light is ON
remote.pressOn();   // Living Room light is ON
remote.pressUndo(); // Living Room light is OFF
```

### Why this is the Command pattern
- `RemoteControl` does not know how a light works.
- It only knows every command has `execute()` and `undo()`.
- You can add more devices/commands later without changing the invoker.

If you want, I can also show a version with a **history stack for multiple undo levels**.

