```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Concurrent;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Reflection;
using System.Text;

public static class FastSerializer
{
    private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<Type, PropertyInfo[]> PropertyCache = new();

    public static string Serialize(object obj)
    {
        if (obj == null) throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(obj));

        var type = obj.GetType();
        var properties = PropertyCache.GetOrAdd(
            type,
            static t => t.GetProperties(BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.Public)
        );

        var sb = new StringBuilder();
        sb.Append('{');

        for (int i = 0; i < properties.Length; i++)
        {
            var prop = properties[i];
            if (i > 0) sb.Append(',');
            sb.Append('"').Append(prop.Name).Append('"').Append(':');

            var value = prop.GetValue(obj);
            sb.Append(value?.ToString() ?? "null");
        }

        sb.Append('}');
        return sb.ToString();
    }
}
```

**Bottleneck**
- The slow part is calling reflection metadata discovery like `type.GetProperties(...)` inside the hot loop for every object.
- That repeatedly scans the type’s metadata and allocates a new `PropertyInfo[]` each time.
- In a serializer, many objects usually share the same runtime type, so rediscovering the same properties is wasted work.

**Optimization**
- Cache the `PropertyInfo[]` per `Type`.
- First time a type is seen: pay the reflection cost once.
- Later serializations of the same type: reuse cached metadata with O(1) average dictionary lookup.
- `ConcurrentDictionary<Type, PropertyInfo[]>` is suitable when serialization may happen from multiple threads.

**Before**
```csharp
public static string SerializeSlow(object obj)
{
    var type = obj.GetType();
    var properties = type.GetProperties(BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.Public);

    var sb = new StringBuilder();
    sb.Append('{');

    for (int i = 0; i < properties.Length; i++)
    {
        var prop = properties[i];
        if (i > 0) sb.Append(',');
        sb.Append('"').Append(prop.Name).Append('"').Append(':');
        sb.Append(prop.GetValue(obj)?.ToString() ?? "null");
    }

    sb.Append('}');
    return sb.ToString();
}
```

**Big-O analysis**
Let:
- `n` = number of objects serialized
- `p` = number of public instance properties on the type

**Before caching**
- Per object:
  - property discovery: `O(p)`
  - iterating properties to read values: `O(p)`
- Total: `O(n * p + n * p) = O(n * p)`
- But with a large constant factor because reflection discovery happens every time.

**After caching**
- First object of a given type:
  - property discovery: `O(p)`
  - serialization walk: `O(p)`
- Each later object of the same type:
  - cache lookup: `O(1)` average
  - serialization walk: `O(p)`
- Total for `n` objects of one type: `O(p) + O(n * p)` = `O(n * p)`

**What improved if Big-O stayed the same?**
- The asymptotic complexity is still dominated by visiting each property value, so Big-O does not fundamentally change.
- The real gain is removing repeated metadata discovery from every iteration.
- Practically:
  - fewer allocations
  - less reflection overhead
  - much lower constant cost in tight loops

